{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628826"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17239"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17239"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77609"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9929"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63122"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10698"},{"type":"tags","id":"10705"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23286"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77609"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring DNA replication, errors can occur that result in changes to the nucleotide sequence. These mutations can affect protein structure and function in different ways.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a non-synonymous mutation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alters RNA splicing sites","Creates alternative start codons","Changes the amino acid sequence","Maintains the same amino acid sequence","Occurs in non-coding DNA regions"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges in the amino acid sequence\u003C/strong\u003E are the defining feature of non-synonymous mutations. These mutations alter the coding sequence in a way that modifies the protein product, either through amino acid substitution (missense mutation) or premature termination (nonsense mutation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlters RNA splicing sites\u003C/strong\u003E - These are splice site mutations which affect pre-mRNA processing rather than coding sequence directly\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreates alternative start codons\u003C/strong\u003E - This would be a specific type of mutation affecting translation initiation, not a non-synonymous mutation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains the same amino acid sequence\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a synonymous or silent mutation where the altered codon still codes for the same amino acid\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccurs in non-coding DNA regions\u003C/strong\u003E - Non-synonymous mutations by definition occur in coding regions and affect protein sequence\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe severity of a non-synonymous mutation\u0027s effect depends on factors such as the chemical properties of the substituted amino acids and their location within functional domains of the protein.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Non-synonymous mutations change the amino acid sequence of the encoded protein.","Missense mutations result in substitution of one amino acid for another, while nonsense mutations create premature stop codons.","The functional impact of non-synonymous mutations depends on the chemical properties of the substituted amino acids and their location in the protein."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63122"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17239"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63122"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:31:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:32:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9929"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77609"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udee7","name":"Cell Biology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}}